          <h2 id="faq">FAQ: VA Loans Under 620 Credit Score</h2>

          <h3>Does the VA require a 620 credit score?</h3>
          <p>No. The VA does not set a minimum credit score for VA-backed home loans. Many lenders set their own minimums, and 620 is common. That is usually a lender overlay, not a VA rule.</p>

          <h3>Can I get a VA loan with a 600 credit score?</h3>
          <p>Possibly, depending on the lender and the full file. Some lenders may review VA borrowers below 620, while others will not. Income, debt, residual income, payment history and recent credit events all matter.</p>

          <h3>Is being denied by one lender the same as being denied by VA?</h3>
          <p>No. A denial from one lender may be based on that lender's overlays, not the VA program itself. Ask whether the issue was a VA rule, an automated underwriting result or the lender's internal requirement.</p>

          <h3>What is a lender overlay?</h3>
          <p>A lender overlay is an extra rule a lender adds on top of the base program guidelines. For example, VA may not require 620, but a lender may set 620 as its own minimum.</p>

          <h3>What is manual underwriting?</h3>
          <p>Manual underwriting is a human review of your loan file when the automated system does not give a clean green light. It may consider payment history, residual income, rent history, savings, debts and explanation letters. It is not automatic.</p>

          <h3>Is my free credit app score the same score a mortgage lender uses?</h3>
          <p>Not necessarily. Free credit apps may show a different score than a mortgage lender uses. Mortgage lenders often review scores from all three major credit bureaus and commonly use the middle score.</p>

          <h3>What if I have no credit score?</h3>
          <p>If you have no credit score or a thin credit file, some lenders may consider alternative credit in manual underwriting. That could include rent, utilities, phone bills or insurance payments. Not all lenders allow this.</p>

          <h3>Can a rapid credit update process help me get over 620?</h3>
          <p>Sometimes, but only in the right situation. A mortgage lender may have a process for updating documented credit-report changes, such as paid-down balances. It does not promise a score increase.</p>

          <h3>Can I use CHFA with a VA loan if my credit is under 620?</h3>
          <p>Usually not. CHFA generally requires a 620 mid-credit score for its homeownership programs. A VA lender may review a lower score, but CHFA has its own separate rules.</p>

          <h3>Can CHAC help if I do not meet CHFA's 620 rule?</h3>
          <p>CHAC may be worth asking about, especially for some borrowers who need counseling or have alternative credit questions. But CHAC is not a guaranteed workaround. It still depends on first mortgage lender approval and CHAC program requirements.</p>

          <h3>Where can I learn more about Colorado homebuyer assistance?</h3>
          <p>Start with the <a href="../../faq.html">Hero HomeReach homebuyer assistance FAQ</a> or explore the <a href="../../programs.html">Colorado homebuyer assistance programs</a> page for plain-English guidance.</p>

